SIMPLE: overcome
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Overcome
<hw>O`ver*come"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Overcame</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Overcome</conjf>; <pos>p. pr & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Overcoming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>ofercuman</ets>. See
<er>Over</er>, <er>Come</er>, and cf. <er>Supervene</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To get the better of; to surmount; to conquer; to
subdue; <as>as, to <ex>overcome</ex> enemies in battle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This wretched woman <qex>overcome</qex>⟦br⟧
Of anguish, rather than of crime, hath been.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To overflow; to surcharge.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>J. Philips.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To come or pass over; to spread over.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>overcome</qex> us like a summer's cloud.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To conquer; subdue; vanquish; overpower;
overthrow; overturn; defeat; crush; overbear; overwhelm; prostrate;
beat; surmount. See <er>Conquer</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overcome</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Overcome
<hw>O`ver*come"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To gain the superiority; to
be victorious.</def> <rj><au>Rev. iii. 21.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overcomer</ent>⟦br⟧
